main event: Multiple sightings of unidentified objects in the vicinity of the moon were reported in New Jersey in March 1959, captured in photographs and witnessed by a professional photographer and amateur astronomer.
interesting points: Multiple saucer-like objects in metallic, silvery-white color were photographed in the field of exposure near the moon, exhibiting a brilliant reflection of light.
The objects appeared in varying sizes and were arranged in directional patterns, with some larger objects closer to the camera and smaller ones further away.
Witnesses, including an experienced photographer and master astronomer, confirmed the unusual appearance of the moon with darkish spots or patches, hinting at an unusual manifestation of activity.

The analysis of the moon-objects photograph by the Air Technical Intelligence Center found the objects to be quite interesting, indicating the quality of the photograph reflected the work of a professional photographer.
The Air Technical Intelligence Center requested the original negative and remainder of the roll film for further analysis, suggesting the potential significance of the captured objects.
sighted object: multiple saucer-like objects in metallic, silvery-white color near the moon
witnesses: professional photographer, amateur astronomer, and a group of neighbors
